 chapters arranged around three organising sub-themes of practice, research and pedagogy. It explores the ‘creative’ component of creative writing in the globalised marketplace, making the point that creative writing occurs in and around universities throughout the world. It examines the convergence of education, globalisation and economic discourses at the intersection of the university sector and creative industries, and foregrounds the competing interests at the core of creativity as it appears in the neo-liberal global discourse in which writers are enmeshed. The book offers case studies from the UK, the USA, Canada, Australia and Singapore that are indicative of the challenges faced by academics, postgraduate students and creative industry professionals around the world.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 31. Jan 2022) 0aCreative writingxStudy and teaching. 7aLANGUAGE ARTS & DISCIPLINES / Writing / General.2bisacsh1 aEdmonds, Phillip, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFisher, Jeremy, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHarper, Graeme, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHarris, Mike, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHecq, Dominique, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHecq, Dominique, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aLappas, Christopher, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMcKenzie, Vahri, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMorris, Robyn, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aPont, Antonia, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aRadia, Pavlina, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aSing